title: Nelson, My Dog
author: susil
text: like the cat he scratches the flea camping in fur.   unlike the cat he delights in water up to his ears.   he frolics.  he catches a crooked stick -  on his back he naps with legs straight up in the air.   nelson shudders awake.  he responds to love  from head to tail.  in happiness  his front legs march in place  and his back legs spark when they push off.   on a leash he knows his geography.   for your sake he looks both ways before crossing,   he sniffs at the sight of a poodle trimmed like a hedge,   and he trots the street with you second in command.   in the park,  he ponders a squirrel attached to a tree  and he shovels a paper cup on his nose.   he sweeps after himself with his tail,   and there is no hand that doesn't deserve a lick.   note this now,  my friends:  nelson can account the heritage of heroic dogs:  one,  canines lead the blind,   two,  they enter fire to rescue the child and the child's toy,   three,  they swim for the drowning,   four,  they spring at the thief,   five,  they paddle ponds for the ball that got away,   six,  for the elderly they walk side by side to the very end,   seven,  they search for bones but stop when called,   eight,  they bring mud to all parties,   nine,  they poke among the ruins of a burnt house,   ten,  they forgive what you dish out on a plate.    nelson is a companion,  this much we know,   and if he were a movie star,  he would do his own stunts -  o,  how he would fly,  climb the pant legs of a scoundrel  and stand tall rafting on white-water rivers!  he has befriended the kingdom of animals:  he once ran with wolves but admittedly not very far,   he stepped two paces into a cave and peeked at the bear,   he sheltered a kitten,   he righted the turtle pedaling its stumps on its back,   under the wheeling stars he caravanned with the mule,   he steered sheep over a hill,   he wisely let the skunk pass,   he growled at the long-bearded miser,   he joined ducks quacking with laughter,   once he leaped at a pheasant but later whined from guilt.    nelson's black nose is a compass in the wilds.   he knows nature.  he has spied spires of summer smoke,   he circled cold campfires,   he howled at a gopher and scratched at the moon,   he doctored his wounds with his tongue,   he has pawed a star of blood left in snow.   he regards the fireplace,  the embers like blinking cats,   this too we know about nelson.   true,  he is sometimes tied to parking meters  and sometimes wears the cone of shame from the vet's office.   but again,  he is happiness.   he presents his belly for a friendly scratch.   if you call him,  he will drop his tennis ball,   look up,  and come running,   this muddy friend for life.  when you bring your nose  to his nose for something like a kiss,   you can find yourself in his eyes.

title: Not in Vane
author: suzanne
text: on september 11th he walked to work  as usual without a thought in the world  as to whether heâ’d ever see his daughter again sweet smiling,  gay laughing,  he went out that day kissing his wife,  and hugging his daughter not making the bed or paying the bills not knowing his last was soon to come   not a thought in his mind as he climbed those tall steps  to the north tower not about the fight that he had with his baby girl     he was a hardy man  who always thought of others  but on that day his time had come  to say goodbye for all time to come as the smoke filed out and the plaster rained down  he worked hard to save others,  down the stairs,  though the halls he guided the people  his motto safety for all  thought he worked hard to save he could save all  so at last he gave up  and called his dear wife to tell her that they  would see each other some day,   in the heavens  above as he drew his last breath he saw above  the gate to heaven,  the angels of mercy and it was there that he realize that he had not failed but had made a difference  when so many had changed the world  for the best or worst,   he knew he had not died in vane  but for his country the united states of america

title: The Middle of my Wood

title: Friendship is Hard
author: tara
text: people say it doesn't happen often.   but i know that's not true.   because i know it happens often  between me and you.    one person starts yelling.   then the other does too.   then we are silent  me and you.    it goes on forever.   without any good signs.   the two of us fighting.   wasting so much time.    being rude and mean.   always making a scene.   the emotions of hatred  and green envy.    but someday it will end.   be sure of that.   but someday it will stop.   and then be flat.    we may not speak now.   though we will soon.   we may not like each other.   our friendship will be ruined.    so stop all this fighting.   go back to the fun.   just you and me  forget everyone   all i have to say.   are two short words.   i'm sorry i mean it sincerely  i didn't want this to occur.

title: A World Poem
author: tarra
text: all of the tragic events in our world,  they happen every day; people dying,  children learning,  and listening to what they say.  they wonder who would do this,  they really do not know,  they're just trying to live a safe life as they grow and grow.  sometimes we just have to stop and think,  about everything going on.  bombs,  guns,  weapons they use,  always scaring us of the terrible news.  it's frightening sometimes,  to know that it's true,  and that it's not just a dream.  if i had one wish,  i would wish it today; i would wish that all of this would stop,  and forever go away.  it's insane what they're doing,  it's selfish and greedy,  they're in their own little world; a world of hurting people together,  which we'll ever understand.  so let them be them,  and let us be us,  we'll go our own separate ways!!

title: Through the Storm
author: tas
text: the thunder crashes.  the lightening flashes.  the wind wails and down comes the hail.   you hug me tight.  you hold me near,  telling me,  ''i am here. ''  i know in rain or snow,  you will calm my fear,  and hold me near.   you tell me.  ''you are safe,  my dear.  so do not fret.  do not pout,  for i am here,  nothing to fear. ''  now i know,  beside me,  you will guide me,  through rain or snow.   the wind's wailing stops.  i hear few drops of rain atop.   the lightening flashes fade    and the thunder no longer crashes.   even when we part,  you'll always be in    my heart.  holding me near,  saying,  ''do not fear    for i am here. ''  guiding me through the storm.

title: Can the lost be found?
author: taycia
text: can the lost be found?  we were close,  but yet far.  had so much in common,  but were so different.  sometimes i wonder,  sometimes i ask myself,  why did we part ways? but then i remember,  the argument.  the terrible argument.  i was mad,  you were scared.  of who i asked you,  the answer was me.  you were not scared of me,  you were scared of my anger,  but all the same it posed a danger.  and the danger was posed,  it was posed on our friendship.  it is gone,  gone to be forgotten.  itâ’s time to move on,  time to forget.  time to begin a new,  but i donâ’t want to and neither do you.  deep inside if you can find,  the burning desire to be higher.  higher then the anger,  higher then the fear,  to be friends again.  just to bring us near.

title: Simple Questions

text: poetry hides in my dogs santa covered mouth.  in the blazing white mp3 player.  and in the tiered up birthday wrapping paper.   poetry hides my tall sky blue downstairs locker.  the brown tied up boots.  and in mackenzie striped green and white t-shirt.   poetry hides the broken cds scattered a cross the room.  in the light purple confider in the blazing hot sun.  and in the big humongous circular belt buckle.   poetry hides in my moms golden rode confider all wrinkled.  the shadowy black boots all rustled up.  and in my whiter than white snow in my snow boots.   poetry hides in the leather maroon couth all shinny.  the silverfish white t/v sitting so still.  and roscoe licking his paws so peacefully.   poetry hides my rustled up green,  white,  & blue scarf.  in the bright hot pink circler paper and in the scatter hearts throw out mrs. koobs room.

title: The World As I See It
author: tristan
text: the crabs of which this world is made of,   are tiny particles in the future.    the future,  is a mindless droning lecture about the world,   and the world to come.    before we can obtain this future,   we must tell a story to god,   so he may let us see it beforehand,   so we may fix what the problem is.    and,   the problem is,   so many drones!   if the world will still be here,   so will thier idiotic family of clones.    if the world really wants to be stupid,   as it will be,   then we have,   not enough to worry about.    as the world turns,   so do the minds.   but only the minds who wish to live.    and those minds,  that wish to live,  will live a long and happy life.    but if they are closed,   those minds will barley even strive to live.    i am a mind that wishes to live,   to strive in the ever populating world.    my voice is to be reached only at random by the person known as me.    i shall guide you from this terror that we call life.   my world,  my rules.

title: The Homeless Stork
author: zachary
text: when i awoke one morning,   a stork was on my head.  i asked,  ''what are you doing on my head?''  it looked at me and said ''i'm just here for a rest. '' so i asked ''why rest on my head i'm sure you have a nest. ''   once he glided on the ground he looked in my eyes and said ''sadly a storm wiped out my woods and now i'm here. '' ''has anyone gave you a room or house to stay in?'' ''no. . . '' said the stork.    i had to think so i said ''if you want you can stay at my place if you want. '' ''thanks'' the stork said in excitement  as i walked and he flew behind me, we talked and bonded. once he had landed on my porch he asked ''can i bring any other friends in. '' ''why sure'' i responded not knowing on the next event. as he walked in he said with a yelp ''come on in!'' as i look out i see dozens of birds storming in all shaped and sizes.
